{
  "text": "A conditional disclosure of secrets (CDS) is a two-message protocol between a client P and a server V where the client learns a secret s specified by the server only if its encrypted inputs x = (x 1 , . . . , x n ) satisfy a public predicate \u03c6(x). The server should learn nothing beyond the vector of encryptions (q 1 , . . . , q n ). We also assume that the client knows the secret key sk or has access to the decryption oracle, whereas the server knows only the public key pk. These protocols are often used as implicit sub-protocols in more complex crypto-computing protocols, see for example [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] .",
